show!

the Black Mountian College show which I thought would be good.
oh yeah, i remember checking it out on their website.  someone else told me that it was a good show.  i may check i out over the holidays.
Do you do installations with your video work?
i have not been to MassMoca.  i really should go.  i've seen reports of some amazing pieces there.
What do you do by day?
no installations, but i have a YouTube channel.  search on grid life experimental electronic video art
Defintiely check MassMoca out. It's a long drive for just a day, but we camp out there when we go. I would also recommend for very different reasons the Clark Institute in Williamstown.

Nice, do you play on a team?

Yes, but I'm terrible at it...Apparently my defense is okay but my hand-eye coordination seems to fail me every time I try to shoot for the basket.
Haha! That's unfortunate. Defense is my favorite part, though.
Why?
I like the challenge of trying to prevent another person from being able to do what they believe they are skilled at doing.
Valid point. Do you have any tips on how to get better at defense or offense?
Improving on defense requires a lot of endurance training, especially with footwork. I would recommend running, doing floor ladders and a lot of defensive slides.
I'm a thrill-seeker so I love bungee jumping, spelunking, sky diving, etc.
That's awesome. I've never experienced any of that, but I think it would be a lot of fun.
It is! It's scary at first but then you get hooked.
Interesting. Which one of those do you enjoy the most?
I think spelunking...it takes a lot of skill and confidence to navigate through a dank, dark cave and to trust your memory to tell you which way is out.
I would not have thought too much about trusting your memory. The confidence part I can definitely understand.
Can you elaborate on what you mean by not thinking too much about trusting memory?
Well, I think I would be so focused on wanting to arrive rather than retaining my focus on retaining the memory of how to get out.
Hm...I guess I get what you mean, but you can still want to arrive while needing to use your memory to figure out how to get out.
Right, I know you need your memory to do it, I just wouldn't have initially thought to describe that experience as trusting your memory. I think you chose a unique way to describe that and I like it.
Thank you! You should try spelunking sometime. (With an experienced person of course.)
I will definitely try it. Finding an experienced person could be an issue. I don't think any of my friends have ever done spelunking.
Good luck! I had the privilege of trying it for the first time at a camp in West Virginia.
Thank you!

Hello!
Hi.  I am female and am a right-wing activist.
I'm also a woman, in college.

I was a college student during the 1970s when many college students were hardcore leftist.  I was a writer and assistant editor for *Ergo* which was a Boston-area college libertarian-conservative newspaper.  Later I wrote for MIT/Wellesley *Counterpoint*.
Do you still write?
I haven't been registered in college since a few courses (Harvard Ukrainian Summer institute, for instance) in the early '90's, but I sit in on lots of courses when I can.
I've actually been writing also on a blog, I'm interested in poetry and creative, reflective non-fiction pieces.

I'd like to see some non-fiction giving insight into the minds of creative people at the moment they create, particularly math and physics people (and not emphasizing the mental deviants as in A Beautiful Mind).

Yes, I think it's interesting to compare the creative process across different disciplines, especially in non-arts fields. I saw a math professor explain his piano composition process, he approached it as a algorithmic process.
Was that Noam Elkies at Harvard?
Yup!

Yes--I've been involved in musical theatre and am working on my own operetta-like work (on WWII mathematicians).  Do you know offhand what was Elkies' operetta -- was it Yossele Solovey or Schlemiel the First?  I confuse them.
No, I'm not sure.
There's a guy out in the western part of the state -- organist -- who teaches algorithm-based composition.  Reminder that I have to meet up with him one of these days.
How would you describe your creative process?

There are lots of different creative processes, and sometimes they compete :-) .  I do a lot of composing at the piano and it almost seems my fingers are doing the work for me.  It's like i've integrated my favorite motifs and chord progressions and the like and my brain/fingers put them together really fast.   Then I also work on paper with designing chord progressions around the circle of fifths, and this has more of a mathematical feel.  I also like impressions (storm clouds, subway) and try to think of what would make those most realistic.
I really enjoy Annie Dillard's work, it's very slow-paced and intensive, but I enjoy how she can draw so much insight and wonder out of a simple moment. I definitely enjoy nature-writing.
Not familiar with Ms. Dillard.  I like nature writing if it has a bit of fear in it -- bristling pine trees as the sun sets, etc.
